Even setting all of these to 1, I still got the same occasional failure. Investigation continues.

{noformat}
one.storage.maxconcurrentsnapshots = 1
one.storage.maxconcurrentsnapshottransfers = 1
one.storage.maxconcurrentvolumes = 1
{noformat}

More info:

* If I do the snap commands concurrently, it fails ~25% of the time, as in:

{noformat}
# euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6 & euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6 & euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6 &
{noformat}

* If I do the snap commands in series, it never fails, as in:

{noformat}
# euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6 && euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6 && euca-create-snapshot vol-9df431f6
{noformat}

* The above info does not change regardless of the maxconcurrent* properties, whether it's 1 or 50.

* The command to rbd to export the snapshot diff (rbd export-diff ...) returns immediately with an error about an invalid argument (but not which one). This indicates one or more of the snap IDs/resources given on the command line by snap deltas code is missing/bad.

* Will next do everything manually with rbd commands. But regardless, there seems to be a concurrency issue in snap (deltas) code because setting the properties to 1 should force Euca to do each snap in series, including the delta, even if rbd export-diff does not support concurrency.

it doesn't appear to have issues with the previous fixes. I think these lines still have a race condition? --
{code:java}

+            if (snapshotPointSemaphore == null) {
+              Integer maxConcurrentSnapshots = StorageInfo.getStorageInfo().getMaxConcurrentSnapshots();
+              int snapshotPointSemaphorePermits = 
+                  (maxConcurrentSnapshots == null ? SNAPSHOT_POINT_DEFAULT_CONCURRENCY : maxConcurrentSnapshots);
+              snapshotPointSemaphore = EucaSemaphoreDirectory.getSemaphore(SNAPSHOT_POINT_SEMAPHORE_KEY, snapshotPointSemaphorePermits);
+   
{code}
 
I guess the fix would be something like...
{code:java}
 Integer maxConcurrentSnapshots = StorageInfo.getStorageInfo().getMaxConcurrentSnapshots();
 int snapshotPointSemaphorePermits = 
                  (maxConcurrentSnapshots == null ? SNAPSHOT_POINT_DEFAULT_CONCURRENCY : maxConcurrentSnapshots);
   snapshotPointSemaphore = EucaSemaphoreDirectory.getSemaphore(SNAPSHOT_POINT_SEMAPHORE_KEY, snapshotPointSemaphorePermits);
{code}
snapshotPointSemaphorePermits could be a class variable to avoid repeated calculations.

[~spark]: Thanks. I can optimize snapshotPointSemaphorePermits as a class var.
The formatting of your proposed code fix makes it unclear to me what you propose to change. Is it the same as what [~sjones] says?

[~sjones]: Yes, I see. Corrected logic?:

{noformat}
      try {
        semaphore.acquire();
      } catch (InterruptedException ex) {
        throw new EucalyptusCloudException("Failed to create snapshot point " + snapshotId + " on volume " + parentVolumeId +
            " as the semaphore could not be acquired");
      }
      try {
        snapshotPointId = rbdService.createSnapshot(parentVolumeId, snapshotPoint, parent.getPool());
      } finally {
        semaphore.release();
      }
{noformat}

If so, then the same wrong logic already exists in SnapshotCreator and VolumeCreator. Should I change those too?
